                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The ogham inscription is cut on a circular stem in the middle of the top third of the pointed pillar. The lower two-thirds are occupied by a pair of <rs type="decoration">Pictish symbols</rs> and traces of a third (Forsyth 1996, 390-1).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>Both inscriptions were <rs type="execution"  key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs> as is typical of Pictich Class I carvings (Forsyth 1996, 391). Strokes are generally evenly spaced and there are generous gaps between letters, though it is important to keep in mind the possibility of distortion due to the circular stem (Forsyth 1996, 396).
                                <height>The shortest letter strokes are 3cm long, the longest are 7cm, and the remainder vary between 4 and 6cm (Forsyth 1996, 393).</height>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
