            <div type="commentary">
                 <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>The placement of the symbols suggests that the ogham was accounted for in the original design, which further implies that the ogham relates to the same phase as the symbols. The stone is a palimpsest as there are visible remains of a partially-erased double-disc and Z-rod under the symbols; however, the overall layout strongly supports the assumption that the ogham relates to the second phase (Forsyth 1996, 391-2).</p>
                    </item>
                    <item n="2"><p>The reading starts from the 10 o'clock position, as this is where the largest gap is located, and continues clockwise (Forsyth 1996, 394).</p>                      
                    </item>
                    <item n="3"><p>Logie is the shortest complete monumental ogham text in Scotland (Forsyth 1996, 398) and as such cannot be readily interpreted. According to Forsyth, the lack of vowels <q>'strongly suggests that the sequence is either encoded, or has no linguistic significance'</q> (ibid).</p>
                    </item>
                 </list>
            </div>
